/**
  @dir rodin/src/
  @brief Source directory for Rodin.
 */

/**
  @dir rodin/src/Rodin
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin
  @brief The Rodin library for finite element methods and shape optimization.

  Rodin is a lightweight and modular C++20 finite element framework providing
  tools for solving partial differential equations and performing shape and
  topology optimization. Key modules include:

  - @ref Rodin::Geometry "Geometry" — Meshes, polytopes, and connectivity
  - @ref Rodin::Variational "Variational" — Finite element spaces, trial/test
    functions, and variational problem formulation
  - @ref Rodin::IO "IO" — Input/output in MFEM, MEDIT, HDF5, and XDMF formats
  - @ref Rodin::Solver "Solver" — Linear and iterative solvers (CG, GMRES, SparseLU)
  - @ref Rodin::Assembly "Assembly" — Assembly of stiffness matrices and load vectors
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/Context
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Context
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Context
  @brief Module for serial, multi-threaded, distributed, and/or parallel
  computation.

  The Context module provides abstractions for different execution environments
  and computing contexts. It enables Rodin to operate efficiently across various
  platforms, from single-machine local execution to distributed computing
  environments.

  ## Supported Contexts
  - **Local Context**: Single-machine execution with shared memory
  - **Distributed Context**: Multi-node execution with message passing (MPI)
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/Alert
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Alert
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Alert
  @brief Module to handle alerts, exceptions, and diagnostic messages.

  The Alert module provides a comprehensive system for handling exceptions,
  warnings, informational messages, and success notifications with colored
  terminal output and formatted messaging capabilities.

  Example usage:
  @code{.cpp}
  Alert::Info() << "Assembling the system..." << Alert::Raise;
  Alert::Success() << "Solution computed successfully." << Alert::Raise;
  @endcode
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/Geometry
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Geometry
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Geometry
  @brief Module for dealing with meshes, polytopes, and geometric operations.

  The Geometry module provides the core data structures for finite element
  meshes. Key classes include:

  - @ref Rodin::Geometry::Mesh "Mesh" — The primary mesh class supporting
    triangular, quadrilateral, tetrahedral, and hexahedral meshes
  - @ref Rodin::Geometry::Polytope "Polytope" — Geometric entities (vertices,
    edges, faces, cells) with type enumeration
  - @ref Rodin::Geometry::Connectivity "Connectivity" — Incidence relations
    between polytopes of different dimensions
  - @ref Rodin::Geometry::Point "Point" — Evaluation point for grid functions

  Meshes can be generated or loaded from files:
  @code{.cpp}
  Mesh mesh;
  mesh = mesh.UniformGrid(Polytope::Type::Triangle, {16, 16});
  mesh.getConnectivity().compute(1, 2); // Compute face-to-cell connectivity
  @endcode
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/Assembly
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Assembly
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Assembly
  @brief Module for performing the assembly of linear algebra objects from
  variational expressions.

  The Assembly module provides the core infrastructure for assembling finite
  element matrices and vectors from variational forms. It supports both
  sequential and parallel assembly strategies, with specializations for
  different operator types and finite element spaces.

  ## Key Features
  - **Bilinear Form Assembly**: Assembly of stiffness matrices from expressions
    like `Integral(Grad(u), Grad(v))`
  - **Linear Form Assembly**: Assembly of load vectors from expressions
    like `Integral(f, v)`
  - **Parallel Assembly**: OpenMP-based parallel assembly
  - **Mixed Formulations**: Support for saddle-point problems (e.g. Stokes)
 */

