/**
  @dir Rodin/Variational
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Variational
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Variational
  @brief Module which provides the necessary tools for constructing and
  solving variational problems.

  The Variational module is the core of the Rodin finite element framework.
  It provides classes for defining finite element spaces, trial and test
  functions, variational forms, boundary conditions, and problems.

  ## Finite Element Spaces

  - @ref Rodin::Variational::P0 "P0" — Piecewise constant (discontinuous)
    finite element space
  - @ref Rodin::Variational::P1 "P1" — Piecewise linear (continuous)
    finite element space
  - @ref Rodin::Variational::H1 "H1" — Higher-order @f$ H^1 @f$-conforming
    finite element space (arbitrary polynomial order)

  ## Functions

  - @ref Rodin::Variational::TrialFunction "TrialFunction" — Represents the
    unknown solution @f$ u @f$ in a variational formulation
  - @ref Rodin::Variational::TestFunction "TestFunction" — Represents the
    weighting function @f$ v @f$
  - @ref Rodin::Variational::GridFunction "GridFunction" — A concrete function
    storing DOF values in a finite element space

  ## Variational Forms

  The module supports building variational problems of the form:
  @f[
    \text{Find} \quad u \in U \quad \text{ s.t. } \quad \forall v \in V \quad
    a(u, v) = b(v) \ ,
  @f]
  which are translated into linear algebra problems @f$ \mathbf{A}\mathbf{x}
  = \mathbf{b} @f$.

  Key expression classes:
  - `Integral(A, B)` — Domain integrals (bilinear or linear forms)
  - `BoundaryIntegral(A, B)` — Boundary integrals
  - `Grad(u)` — Gradient operator
  - `Div(u)` — Divergence operator
  - `Jacobian(u)` — Jacobian operator
  - `DirichletBC(u, g)` — Dirichlet boundary conditions

  ## Problem

  The @ref Rodin::Variational::Problem "Problem" class assembles all forms
  and boundary conditions into a solvable linear system.

  @code{.cpp}
  P1 Vh(mesh);
  TrialFunction u(Vh);
  TestFunction  v(Vh);

  Problem poisson(u, v);
  poisson = Integral(Grad(u), Grad(v))
          - Integral(f, v)
          + DirichletBC(u, Zero());

  Solver::CG(poisson).solve();
  @endcode

  @see @ref guides-variational "Variational Formulations Guide"
 */

