/**
  @dir Rodin/Eikonal
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Eikonal
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Eikonal
  @brief Module which provides solvers for the Eikonal equation.

  The Eikonal equation is a non-linear partial differential equation of the form:
  @f[
    |\nabla u| = F(x)
  @f]
  where @f$ F(x) @f$ is a speed function. When @f$ F = 1 @f$, the solution
  represents the distance function. This module provides efficient Fast Marching
  Method (FMM) implementations for solving the Eikonal equation on unstructured
  meshes.
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/Elasticity
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Elasticity
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Elasticity
  @brief Module which provides models for solid mechanics and elasticity.

  This module implements various elasticity models including linear elasticity
  for small deformations. Key functionality:

  - `LinearElasticityIntegral(u, v)(lambda, mu)` — Assembles the bilinear form
    for linearized elasticity with Lamé parameters @f$ \lambda @f$ and @f$ \mu @f$

  @see @ref examples-pdes-elasticity "Elasticity example"
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/QF
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::QF
 */

/**
  * @namespace Rodin::QF
  * @brief Module for defining quadrature formulae.

  * The QF (Quadrature Formula) module provides numerical integration rules
  * for computing integrals over reference polytopes. These quadrature rules
  * approximate integrals by weighted sums:
  * @f[
  *   \int_K f(x) \, dx \approx \sum_{i=1}^n w_i f(x_i)
  * @f]
  * where @f$ K @f$ is a reference polytope, @f$ x_i @f$ are quadrature points,
  * and @f$ w_i @f$ are associated weights.
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/FormLanguage
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::FormLanguage
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::FormLanguage
  @brief Module for writing high level abstract expressions.

  The FormLanguage module provides the expression template infrastructure
  underlying Rodin's variational form language. It enables composing
  mathematical expressions that are lazily evaluated during assembly:

  @code{.cpp}
  auto stiffness = Integral(Grad(u), Grad(v)); // expression, not yet evaluated
  auto load = Integral(f, v);                   // another expression
  Problem p(u, v);
  p = stiffness - load + DirichletBC(u, Zero()); // combined expression
  @endcode
 */

/**
  @dir Rodin/Math
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Math
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Math
  @brief Module for general mathematical operations.

  Provides mathematical constants, vector/matrix types, and utility functions.
  Key items include:

  - `Math::Constants::pi()` — The constant @f$ \pi @f$
  - `Math::Vector<Real>` — Dense vector type
  - `Math::Matrix<Real>` — Dense matrix type
 */


/**
  @dir Rodin/Solver
  @brief Namespace @ref Rodin::Solver
 */

/**
  @namespace Rodin::Solver
  @brief Module for solving linear and nonlinear systems.

  The Solver module provides linear solvers for the systems arising from
  finite element discretizations. Available solvers include:

  - @ref Rodin::Solver::CG "CG" — Conjugate Gradient (for SPD systems)
  - @ref Rodin::Solver::GMRES "GMRES" — Generalized Minimum Residual
  - @ref Rodin::Solver::SparseLU "SparseLU" — Direct sparse LU factorization
  - @ref Rodin::Solver::UMFPack "UMFPack" — UMFPACK direct solver

  Usage:
  @code{.cpp}
  // Iterative solver
  Solver::CG(problem).solve();

  // Direct solver
  Solver::SparseLU(problem).solve();
  @endcode

  @see @ref guides-variational "Variational Formulations Guide"
 */

